  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2670794446" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2670794446" />
    <a title="CLAR" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/30833057-clar"><img alt="CLAR" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1621697828p2/30833057.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2670794446?book_show_action=true">Apr 11, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="CLAR" class="user" itemprop="url" name="CLAR" href="/user/show/30833057-clar">CLAR</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="ebook " href="/book/show/31677792-in-the-distance-there-is-light">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2670794446" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer277366154483706407">First of all, writing a book like this was a risk. As a reader, I took note of that risk and tried to see past the taboo out of complete curiosity as to how the author would turn this into a workable plot.<br/><br/>As with all tales of romances, one of the most important elements to make it successful is the development of chemistry between two people before either one blurts out that much-expected four-letter word. But the thing is, timing and buildup play a huge role in this. You can&apos;t just make a chara</span>
  <span id="freeText277366154483706407" style="display:none">First of all, writing a book like this was a risk. As a reader, I took note of that risk and tried to see past the taboo out of complete curiosity as to how the author would turn this into a workable plot.<br /><br />As with all tales of romances, one of the most important elements to make it successful is the development of chemistry between two people before either one blurts out that much-expected four-letter word. But the thing is, timing and buildup play a huge role in this. You can't just make a character say, "This is love," and make the reader believe that it is. And that's the huge problem with this book. It's all tell and barely show. I understand a first-person narrative has its own appeal. But what this book suffered from is its failure to go beyond Sophie's musings. We are forced to look at this world from her point of view, and it bothers me that she wasn't able to offer much more than what we already know. Her thoughts were repetitive and self-centered. They're nothing more than validations of previously established facts. Her character wasn't likeable nor interesting. She was way inside her head, too absorbed in her own thoughts, that she robbed us of the experience to see the story as it plays out. <br /><br />Furthermore, we know Sophie and Dolores were brought closer together by Ian's death from the beginning. But I hated how much his death defined the women's relationship. His death was all over the story. From start to finish. Talks about moving on were mentioned here and there, yet Sophie's reflections failed to convey or prove that that's what she and Dolores were really doing. Like, how can you convince me that <b>this is love</b> when you can't even see the woman in front of you without first thinking of her dead son?<br /><br />In the end, all I can really say is, at least I gave this a chance. I was open-minded about the premise. But nope, the execution flunked. Big time.</span>
  <a data-text-id="277366154483706407" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

